Commenting about the development, Judiciary spokesperson Jameson Karemani said, “It is true that Mr Kyagulanyi’s lawyers had written to the court to allow them to file their petition today (Saturday) but the Chief Justice advised that they file it on Monday.”
Time factor
Mr Kyagulanyi’s lawyers are racing against time because the law gives an aggrieved candidate a maximum of 15 days after the results have been released to file a petition. 
The results were declared on January 16, meaning the 15 days expire on Sunday, but since it is a weekend, the Chief Justice has allowed the filing of the petition on Monday.



