Mr Kyagulanyi disputes the results that the Electoral Commission (EC) has published, showing that President Museveni was re-elected with 58.38 per cent of the votes in the January 14 polls. 
He came second with 35.08 per cent while the rest of the votes were shared by the remaining nine candidates. 
Decision to go to court
The matter of whether or not to challenge the election result in court has been a contentious one within Mr Kyagulanyi’s camp, with some saying it is a waste of time and that they don’t expect the Supreme Court, which has not annulled any of Mr Museveni’s three victories that were challenged in the past, will do so this time round.



